English plural word<n>2. English plural form will get you plural forms<n><n>#### Solution:<n><n>##### 1. English Plural Noun<n>The method will be as follows:<n>1. For each word, compare the word with all words from the "ENGLISH PLURAL NORMS"<n>2. If a match is found, then the word can be added to the set of words.<n>3. If a word is matched, then the words are placed in the order they were matched. For example, "shirt" will be added before "shirts".<n><n>##### 2. English Plural Form<n>The method will be following:<n>1. For plural form words:<n> a. If a plural form word ends in a consonant, the consonant will be doubled. If there is no vowel, the vowel "I" will be added to the word<n> b. If a plural word ends in consonant "S", the S will remain to not make it a plural form.<n> c. Words that don't end in vowel or S will not be converted. However, plural form does not need to be added to these words.<n>2. For non-plural form words in the current list

### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Fabric is cut to order at what type of seller? Choices:  A: curtains B: tailor shop C: clothing store D: sewing room E: hardware store<n>Output: B: tailor shop<n><n>Input: Where are you if your reading magazines while waiting for a vehicle on rails? Choices:  A: ground B: human  body C: repair shop D: combustion engines E: service station<n>Output: D: combustion engines<n><n>Input: What is person probably feeling that plans on stopping being married to their spouse? Choices:  A: detachment B: bankruptcy C: sad D: fights E: wrong<n>Output: A: detachment<n><n>Input: What could you use to store a clock? Choices:  A: shelf B: own bedroom C: desk D: wall E: car<n>Output: A: shelf<n><n>Input: The person put on lotion, what did they want? Choices:  A: fresh smell B: good credit C: smooth skin D: fresh produce E: headache<n>Output: C: smooth skin<n><n>Input:The shelf was showing signs of instability, what should the carpenter fix to avoid any issues? Choices:  A: roof B: corner C: school building D: wall E: cupboard<n>Output:		E: cupboard<n><n>Input:When are you making music with a brass section? Choices:  IA: spring I: early summer A: late summer<n>Output: I: late summer<n>  ### Explanation (If it takes too long to read, just run your code and see what happens)<n>  The key is to test for the value of the character.<n><n>  A: Character is an ascii value between 48 and 57<n>  B: Character is any digit (not 0 to 9) or space<n>  B: Character = " " or "-", and if not an alphabetical character, then it's a capitalised character<n>  D: Capitalised character is any character between 65 to 90<n>  E: "." and ",", except they may still turn into periods or commas when they can<n>  All characters on the right and the left of one of the sets on the left.<n><n>  If the character on the left is a digit or space, and the one on the right is not a capitalised letter or digit, it is either a word character or not a word character, so check one of the "or"s accordingly.<n><n>  Other rules (like word character is only a letter, or capitalised word characters are any of the upper or lower case versions of a capitalised letter) are redundant, as word character becomes either a capitalised word character, or a word character otherwise.<n>

### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Fabric is cut to order at what type of seller? Choices:  A: curtains B: tailor shop C: clothing store D: sewing room E: hardware store<n>Output: B: tailor shop<n><n>Input: Where are you if your reading magazines while waiting for a vehicle on rails? Choices:  A: vegetables B: market C: doctor D: train station E: bookstore<n>Output: D: train station<n><n>Input: What would need oil to be used? Choices:  A: ground B: human  body C: repair shop D: combustion engines E: service station<n>Output: D: combustion engines<n><n>Input: What is person probably feeling that plans on stopping being married to their spouse? Choices:  A: detachment B: bankruptcy C: sad D: fights E: wrong<n>Output: A: detachment<n><n>Input: What could you use to store a clock? Choices:  A: shelf B: own bedroom C: desk D: wall E: car<n>Output: A: shelf<n><n>Input: The person put on lotion, what did they want? Choices:  A: fresh smell B: good credit C: smooth skin D: fresh produce E: headache<n>Output: C: smooth skin<n><n>Input:What is a parents primary duty? Choices:  A: speak freely B: happiness of a child C: care for children D: school child E: control children<n>Output:		C: care for children<n><n>Input: What will you need to get at a pharmacy? Choices:  I: medication II: prescription III: pills IV: aspirin V: pain medication<n>Output: I: medication<n><n># Solution 1<n>def solution1():<n>    s=input()<n>    ans=[0]*len(s)<n>    temp[0]=-2<n>    m=[-2 for _ in range(len(s))]<n>    for i in range(len(temp)):<n>        if s[i][0] == '#':<n>            temp[i]+=1<n>        elif s[i][0].isdigit():<n>            for p in range(len(m)):<n>                m[p]+=1<n>    p=-1<n>    while p<len(s):<n>        s=temp[s[p]]<n>        s=sorted(s)<n>        if ',' in s[-1]:<n>            ans[p]=1+s.count(s[-2])<n>        else:<n>            ans[p]=-2<n>            for i in range(p):<n>                if s[i]=="1":<n>                    ans[p]=-1<n>        print(ans[p])<n>        p+=1<n>solution1()<n><n># Solution 2<n>def solution2():<n>    a=[0]*len(input())<n>    n=(len(a))<n>    a[0]=-2;<n>    for i in a[:]:<n>        if a[i]==None:<n>            temp2[i]=-1<n>    count1=[len(t) for t in a]<n>    for i in temp2:<n>        if i==None:<n>            print(-1)<n>            continue<n>        if a[count1.index(len(a)-i-1)].isdigit():<n>    print(a[b].count(a[b-2])+0-1)*i<n>    elif a[count1.last_index(len(a) - i - 1)].isdigit() or (a[count1.last].isdigit() and a[count1.first].isdigit()):<n>        print(a[b]+a[b-2]** -2)<n>solution2()<n>

Choices:  A: detachment B: bankruptcy C: sad D: fights E: wrong<n>Output: A: detachment<n><n>Input: What could you use to store a clock? Choices:  A: play chess B: sun themselves C: wrong house D: set table E: gettable<n>Output:		E: gettable<n><n>-----<n><n><n>### Solution:<n>---<n><n>```cpp<n>int main()<n>{<n>    long long ans = 0;<n><n>    int a = 0, b = 0, c = 0;<n>    <n>    if(b < 100) {<n>        c = 1;<n>    } <n><n>    while(a < 30 && b < 75 && c < 100){ <n>        ans++;<n>        b++;<n>        <n>    }<n>    return ans;<n>}<n>```<n>

So a lot of sugar is found in a refrigerator. This is what is meant by fresh smell and good credit.<n>

### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Fabric is cut to order at what type of seller? Choices:  A: curtains B: tailor shop C: clothing store D: sewing room E: hardware store<n>Output: B: tailor shop<n><n>Input: Where are you if your reading magazines while waiting for a vehicle on rails? Choices:  A: detachment B: bankruptcy C: sad D: fights E: wrong<n>Output: A: detachment<n><n>Input: What could you use to store a clock? Choices:  A: shelf B: own bedroom C: desk D: wall E: car<n>Output: A: shelf<n><n>Input: The person put on lotion, what did they want? Choices:  A: fresh smell B: good credit C: smooth skin D: fresh produce E: headache<n>Output: C: smooth skin<n><n>Input:What is a person chatting with friends likely hoping to accomplish? Choices:  A: gathering of information B: communication C: feel relaxed D: kill boredom E: social bonding<n>Output:		C: feel relaxed<n><n>Input: What does the sentence 'It was my pleasure' show? Choices:  B: disinterest. C: sympathy.<n>Output: B: disinterest<n><n>Input: Where is a person likely going if they are looking at a calendar? Choices:  C: bank D: store E: church<n>Output: D: store<n><n>#### Explanation:<n><n>- 1. The fabric is cut to order at a cloth store, where a tailor shop is one of the best types of stores if you are ordering custom cuts to your personalized requests.<n>- 2. The customer is in a book store as he's reading magazines. A book store is where people stop by to read the magazine of their choice, they're not likely to be waiting for a vehicle on rail. The magazine is most likely about a journey by train.<n>- 3. Oil is what is required for cars, engines, cars, motorcycles are the types of motorized vehicles that use oil. Oil can come in a variety of types, and so could be used for various purposes. The person could be referring to the fact that their spouse is using oil, or that they are a mechanic who would need to use oil for their job.<n>- 4. A clock could be kept in a shelf. A bedroom can become extremely cluttered and full of things, whereas a shelf would be much easier to keep in order, organized.<n>- 5. Smooth skin indicates that the person put lotion on their face after washing it.<n>- 6. The person likely wanted to kill boredom with their friends, most likely this was done by social bonding, when people talk to each other.<n>- 7. The speaker is not interested in the situation they are in, and so they speak this way.<n>- 8. The person could be going to church if they look at the calendar.<n>- 9. A book store is a place to read the magazine of your choice. You're not likely to find a bookstore that's open 9am - 5pm on the weekends. You find places like that for cars, and trains.<n>- 10. A friend is a possible outcome for the person who was chatting with their friends as they killed their boredom.<n>

### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Fabric is cut to order at what type of seller? Choices:  A: curtains B: tailor shop C: clothing store D: sewing room E: hardware store<n>Output: B: tailor shop<n><n>Input: Where are you if your reading magazines while waiting for a vehicle on rails? Choices:  A: vegetables B: market C: doctor D: train station E: bookstore<n>Output: D: train station<n><n>Input: What would need oil to be used? Choices:  A: ground B: human  body C: repair shop D: combustion engines E: service station<n>Output: D: combustion engines<n><n>Input: What is person probably feeling that plans on stopping being married to their spouse? Choices:  A: detachment B: bankruptcy C: sad D: fights E: wrong<n>Output: A: detachment<n><n>Input: What could you use to store a clock? Choices:  A: shelf B: own bedroom C: desk D: wall E: car<n>Output: A: shelf<n><n>Input: The person put on lotion, what did they want? Choices:  A: fresh smell B: good credit C: smooth skin D: fresh produce E: headache<n>Output: C: smooth skin<n><n>Input:A night owl is what you'd head at sunset and you'd hear a what at sunrise? Choices:  A: morning person B: early bird C: lark D: early riser E: rooster<n>Output:		E: rooster<n><n>Input: What's likely to happen to a plant if it doesn't have enough sunlight? Choices: <n>A: will be roasted B: can wilt C: can dry D: can wither E: can shrivel<n>Output: A: will be roasted</p><n><p>Instruction: The first line gives the number of questions from I to Q, and the second line contains Q questions each separated by a space. For each question, give three possible answers.<n>The answer is a string of length 1 where the elements range from [0, 3].</p><n><n>[code]<n>class Solution:<n>    def myPlainTextAnswer(self, question: str, answer: str) -> str:<n>        answer_list = answer.split(" ")<n>        ans0 = answer_list[0]<n>        ans1 = answer_list[1]<n>        ans2 = answer_list[2]<n>        ans_list = [ans0, ans1, ans2]<n>        ans = " ".join(str(a) for a in ans_list)<n>        return ans<n><n>```<n>

### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Fabric is cut to order at what type of seller? Choices:  A: curtains B: tailor shop C: clothing store D: sewing room E: hardware store<n>Output: B: tailor shop<n><n>Input: Where are you if your reading magazines while waiting for a vehicle on rails? Choices:  A: vegetables B: market C: doctor D: train station E: bookstore<n>Output: D: train station<n><n>Input: What would need oil to be used? Choices:  A: ground B: human  body C: repair shop D: combustion engines E: service station<n>Output: D: combustion engines<n><n>Input: What is person probably feeling that plans on stopping being married to their spouse? Choices:  A: detachment B: bankruptcy C: sad D: fights E: wrong<n>Output: A: detachment<n><n>Input: What could you use to store a clock? Choices:  A: shelf B: own bedroom C: desk D: wall E: car<n>Output: A: shelf<n><n>Input: The person put on lotion, what did they want? Choices:  A: fresh smell B: good credit C: smooth skin D: fresh produce E: headache<n>Output: C: smooth skin<n><n>Input:What might two people competing get into? Choices:  A: stress B: debate C: argument D: winning or losing E: tension<n>Output:		A: stress<n><n>## Solution:<n>```python<n>from collections import Counter<n>from operator import itemgetter<n><n># First we convert all the question to lowercase<n>questions = list(map(str.lower, open("questions.in")))<n><n># Next we convert all the letters into their index.<n># We do this by having a set of all the characters in the test.<n>all_characters = set('0123456789.a-fA-F')<n>character_map = dict.fromkeys(all_characters, i)<n>all_characters.update(character_map.values())<n><n>ans = [word for word in character_map.values() if word in answers]<n><n>ans_counter = Counter(ans)<n><n># Now we convert the answers that are repeated<n>answers = list(ans_counter.most_common(1)[:5])<n>answers_dict = dict(answers)<n>answers = [answers_dict[key] for key in answers]<n><n># We next remove all the characters from the answser list that aren't in the answers dict.<n>answers = [letter for letter in answers if letter in all_characters]<n><n>answer_char_map = {letter : i for i, letter in enumerate(character_map.items())}<n>answers = [answer_char_map[letter] for letter in list(question[::-1])]<n><n>answers = list([' '.join(x) for x in set(answers)])<n>correct = 0<n><n># This loop is like a switch case<n>for word in questions:<n>   if word in answers:<n>        if answer_correct(word, answer):<n>            correct+=1<n>    return(correct)<n><n>def answer_correct(inp, match):<n>    return(inp == question[-1])<n><n>```<n>

### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Fabric is cut to order at what type of seller? Choices:  A: curtains B: tailor shop C: clothing store D: sewing room E: hardware store<n>Output: B: tailor shop<n><n>Input: Where are you if your reading magazines while waiting for a vehicle on rails? Choices:  A: vegetables B: market C: doctor D: train station E: bookstore<n>Output: D: train station<n><n>Input: What would need oil to be used? Choices:  A: ground B: human  body C: repair shop D: combustion engines E: service station<n>Output: D: combustion engines<n><n>Input: What is person probably feeling that plans on stopping being married to their spouse? Choices:  A: detachment B: bankruptcy C: sad D: fights E: wrong<n>Output: A: detachment<n><n>Input: What could you use to store a clock? Choices:  A: shelf B: own bedroom C: desk D: wall E: car<n>Output: A: shelf<n><n>Input: The person put on lotion, what did they want? Choices:  A: fresh smell B: good credit C: smooth skin D: fresh produce E: headache<n>Output: C: smooth skin<n><n>Input:Where would you put a light? Choices:  A: ocean B: desk C: universe D: attic E: chair<n>Output:		A: ocean<n><n>### Solution<n><n>Solution: ```import pandas as pd; import re```<n><n>#### Question: Answer the following multiple choice question<n><n>Input: Fabic is cut to order at which type of seller?<n><n>Output should be B: tailor shop.<n><n>Input: Where is the person reading magazines while they waiting for a train?<n><n>Output: A: vegetables<n><n>Input: What does the person need to oil?<n><n>output D: combustion engine<n><n>Input: How is a married person feeling?<n><n>Output: Detachment<n><n>Input: Which place would you use to store a pocket clock<n><n>Output: A shelf<n><n>Input  Which place would you put on a light<n><n>Output: A Ocean<n>    <n>### Question: Answer the following question<n><n>#### Solution:<n>```import pandas as pd; from collections import defaultdict;<n>p_dict = defaultdict(int)<n><n>line = re.compile('.*?(\d+).*?(\d+).+?\((\d+)\).*')<n><n><n>with open('data.txt') as data_file:<n>    for line in data_file:<n>        words = re.split(' ')<n>        <n>        customer_number = p_dict[words[0]]<n>        product_number = p_disc[words[1]]<n>        location = words[2]<n>        price = int(words[3])<n><n>        if line == product_sold:<n>            print(product_sold.format(customer_number,  product_number,  location))<n>        elif line == product_purchased:<n>            print(customer_number.format(product_number,' '), end='')<n>        elif line == price:<n>            print('\n-' * len(price))<n>            print(f"  {p_dict[location]}") <n>    print('-----------------------------------')<n>    print('-------------------')<n>```<n><n>

### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Fabric is cut to order at what type of seller? Choices:  A: curtains B: tailor shop C: clothing store D: sewing room E: hardware store<n>Output: B: tailor shop<n><n>Input: Where are you if your reading magazines while waiting for a vehicle on rails? Choices:  A: vegetables B: market C: doctor D: train station E: bookstore<n>Output: D: train station<n><n>Input: What would need oil to be used? Choices:  A: ground B: human  body C: repair shop D: combustion engines E: service station<n>Output: D: combustion engines<n><n>Input: What is person probably feeling that plans on stopping being married to their spouse? Choices:  A: detachment B: bankruptcy C: sad D: fights E: wrong<n>Output: A: detachment<n><n>Input: What could you use to store a clock? Choices:  A: shelf B: own bedroom C: desk D: wall E: car<n>Output: A: shelf<n><n>Input: The person put on lotion, what did they want? Choices:  A: fresh smell B: good credit C: smooth skin D: fresh produce E: headache<n>Output: C: smooth skin<n><n>Input:The man needed balls of cotton, where should he look? Choices:  A: south B: georgia C: north carolina D: pocket E: medicine cabinet<n>Output:		A: south<n>```<n><n>The above examples were just a few of a many examples you can find by using the `train_datagen()` python function of TensorFlow. This function is used to give you as a teacher/learner input, which will then determine what machine learning model you should use to solve the problem. This is done with a `train_and_predict()` function, where you need to know the correct answer, which will tell you, when you have finished your training, how successful or unsuccessful it was. If it is successful, it will have a high accuracy. You then save this output as, for example: Accuracy=0.98, loss=0.16, which you can use as an example before you get the model working perfectly.<n><n>After getting the model working perfectly, you will need the training data to work with. Now, this might seem to be pretty straight forward. All you have to do is to input this information into your machine learning program. Which of course, you should do, but it should help you understand why most companies tend to buy this kind of information! This information is valuable, so you should probably know how can you determine if the kind of data you are working with is clean or not. <n><n>### Cleaning data<n><n>Now, in the case above, you might start to do the work yourself. So what are you looking for when you are determining clean or dirty data, and how can you clean up the messy machine learning data without changing the meaning of the data itself? <n><n>If you ask a couple of companies, you get quite different opinions. Some would say: **you should only work with clean data**, some would say: **you don’t have to work only with clean data, you just have to clean up the messy data yourself**. <n><n>The difference between these two opinions is basically: how to interpret the information. What one person thinks is clean data, another person will think is a mess. So instead of trying to clean the data, by making sure that everything is in order, just do something about the meaning.<n><n>There is, however, some things that you should do:<n><n>1. **Grammar and spelling**<n><n><n>This is sometimes a difficult one. But you should know that grammar is a basic way to identify dirty data. When using your machine learning to work with data or making predictions,

E: work<n>Output:		A: business<n>#### Evaluation Code:<n><n>```<n>// This is the evaluation code in pycharm - note that the evaluation code doesn't match the instructions.<n>def __init__(self):<n>        #self.answer = []<n>        self._question = []<n><n>        with open('../input.txt') as question_file:<n>            for line in question_file.readlines():<n>                line = line.strip()<n>                try:<n>                    self.process_line(line)<n>                    print("Processed line:", line)<n>                except Exception as e:<n>                    print(e)<n><n>def process_line(self, line):<n>    self._question.append(line)<n><n>def get_answer(self):<n>    return self.answer<n><n>def start_run(self, solution_code):<n>    """<n>        Initializes and runs the current session.<n>        The session runs for until it the evaluation code returns True.<n>    :param solution_code:<n>    :return:<n>    """<n>    self.__init__()<n><n>    # Evaluates the evaluation code<n>    while not self.process_line():<n>        pass<n><n>    # Evalutes the real data<n>    answer = []<n>    with open('../input_data.txt') as data_file:<n>        for line in data_file.readlines() + '\n':<n>            line = line.split('\t')<n>            for key, value in line:<n>                value = int(value)  # str is not the same as int<n>                answer.append(((int(key), value)))<n>        print("Answer:", answer)<n>        print("Result:", answer)<n>    # Evalutate the answer<n>    print("Result:", self._question)<n>    print("Result answer:", answer)<n><n>## main method for testing<n><n>def main():<n>    # Instantiate a new class and start to run it<n>    answer = Classification_Tester()<n>    answer.start_run(solution_code)<n>    # TODO start solving and run, run, run until your done<n>```<n><n>### Test your code on Test cases:<n><n>Input: What must you be able to do before driving a truck? Choices:  A: dairy farm B: texas C: building D: michigan E: florida<n>Output:		B: texas<n>input: What did the people do when the elevator stopped? Choices:  B: they got in the car C: they got angry D: they went to the beach E: they called an Uber<n>Output: A: they got angry<n>input: What could a student bring if you were going camping? Choices:  C: computer B: blanket D: camera E: food<n>Output: B: blanket<n><n>#!/bin/bash<n>[ $# -ne 0 ] && { echo "Usage: $0 [Question]" 1>&2 && exit 1; }<n>#$# = Number of arguments.<n>echo "========= ANSWERS: =========="<n>cat answ1.csv<n>echo "============================ "<n>cat answ2.csv<n>echo "========= CORRECT ANSWERS: === "<n>cat answ3.csv<n>answer="$1"<n>echo $answer<n>cate="$(cat answ1.txt)"<n>slt="$(sed "s/s/\.csv//g" "$anws1.ct")"<n>sed -n "$slt<n><n>echo $cate<n>echo $answer<n>[ "$answer" == "$cate" ] && echo "Correct" || echo "Incorrect"<n>echo "========= OUTPUT: ==========="<n>echo $answer` "$cate<n>echo $slt<n>echo $answer <n>[ ${answer#*"$cate"} = $cate ] && echo "Corre"<n>
### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Fabric is cut to order at what type of seller? Choices:  A: curtains B: tailor shop C: clothing store D: sewing room E: hardware store<n>Output: B: tailor shop<n><n>Input: Where are you if your reading magazines while waiting for a vehicle on rails? Choices:  A: vegetables B: market C: doctor D: train station E: bookstore<n>Output: D: train station<n><n>Input: What would need oil to be used? Choices:  A: ground B: human  body C: repair shop D: combustion engines E: service station<n>Output: D: combustion engines<n><n>Input: What is person probably feeling that plans on stopping being married to their spouse? Choices:  A: detachment B: bankruptcy C: sad D: fights E: wrong<n>Output: A: detachment<n><n>Input: What could you use to store a clock? Choices:  A: shelf B: own bedroom C: desk D: wall E: car<n>Output: A: shelf<n><n>Input: The person put on lotion, what did they want? Choices:  A: fresh smell B: good credit C: smooth skin D: fresh produce E: headache<n>Output: C: smooth skin<n><n>Input:Utensils are used during what evening activity? Choices:  A: backpack B: closet C: drawer D: dinner E: cupboard<n>Output:		D: dinner<n><n>Input: What's wrong with this toaster? Choices:  B: bread not in the top B: bread to warm A: toast too dark C: missing power cord E: butter not in toaster<n>Output: A: toast too brown<n>```<n>```python<n>class Solution(object):<n>    def findWords(self, words, pictograms):<n>        """<n>        :type words: List[str]<n>        :type pictograms: List[str] <n>        :rtype: List[str]  <n>        """<n>        lam = len(words)<n>        result = []<n>        for word in pictograms:    <n>            for char in word:<n>                result.append(words[char-65])<n>        return result<n>```<n><n>## Python<n><n>import pyspark.sql as ps<n>from pyspark.sql import functions as sql_f<n>import string<n><n>words = ["sugar", "tea", "cup", "coffee"]<n>pictograms = ['tea and cup', 'coffee maker', 'toast','micro', 'kitch', "cupboard", "closet", "drawer", "shelf", "sink", "desk", "bedroom", "dining"]<n><n>df = ps.read.format('csv').option("header",True).load('../input.csv')<n><n><n>output_df = df.select(<n>    df["label"].alias("label"),<n>    df["words"].alias("pic"),<n>    df.select(sql_f.split(" ",df["words"]).alias("words")).join(<n>        df.select(words).alias("words")<n>       .where("words == label"), on="label "<n>    ).alias("ans")<n>).withColumn("pic_words",df["pic"].contains(df["ans"]))<n><n>def f(w): # function to return if the string is in the word list<n>    if w in words:<n>        return 1<n>    else:<n>        return 0<n><n>    pictograms.map(lambda x: [x])<n>    output_df = df.withColumn('words',sql_f.split(df["pic"],'').alias('words'))

Choices:  D: the bathroom  T: the carport  M: the dining room  L: the room  N: the closet  G: the living room<n>Output: G: the living room\<n>### Solution:<n><n>```rust<n>    use std::io::{stdin, stdout}<n>    struct Solution {}<n><n>    impl Solution {<n>        pub fn check(lines: Vec<(&str, &str)>) -> i32 {<n>              let lines: Vec<(String, String)> = lines.into_iter().map(|(i, j)| {<n>                    let i: &str = i;<n>                    let j: &str = j;<n>                    (i.to_lowercase(), j.to_lowercase())<n>                }).collect();<n>                let mut counter: u64 =0;<n>                for x in &lines {<n>                    let answer = match  x.0.find(x.1) {<n>                        Some(y) => y as u64,<n>                        None => 0,<n>                    };<n>                    counter += answer;<n>                }<n>                let mut answer = 0;<n>                for each_word in lines{<n>                    answer = answer + &each_word.1;<n>                    match answer{<n>                        Some(v)=>{<n>                            if counter==v {<n>                                println!("Yes");<n>                            }<n>                            else{<n>                                println!("no");<n>                            }                        <n>                        },<n>                        None=>{<n>

Choices: A: feet B: wheel C: miles D: meter E: centimeter<n>Output: B:  wheel<n><n>__Answer 1:__ _B_ The "tailor shop" is a specialty store. These types of retailers sell smaller volumes of higher-value merchandise, often in specialized locations. A tailor shop will be found in or near clothing stores, or in areas where customers are likely to have clothes that need altering. This includes places like grocery stores and clothing stores and on or near college campuses. By contrast, hardware stores typically carry much larger quantities of commodity products that can be sold in lower volumes. An example of a commodity product would be an outdoor shovel. Hardware stores carry very few outdoor shovels and many customers will choose from among a dozen different brands, based on their quality. They also may use a brand of shovel that they already know and trust. <n><n>__Answer 2:__ _B_ In this question, "waiting for a train" and "on rails" are meant to be used in the same sense as "waiting at a train station" and "on rails". We know the answer is "waiting for a vehicle on rails", however, we would need to look for an unnatural phrase that uses the same terms (on/waiting for a/vehicle on rails), such as "waiting for a subway" or "waiting for a bus". This type of word play is rarely used, and is used less frequently by native speakers. This question contains a wordplay where words like "vehicle" and "on rails", and "waiting" and "for a" are similar. However,

You used some images that made the text very hard to read.<n><n>Answer: You should try [Folium](https://www.tensorflow.org/lite/examples/python/folium) to plot in TensorFlow.<n><n>For your question "What kind of seller has Fabric for sale?", I would interpret it as asking how to classify from one class to another. A classifier is a predictor that given the "question" (in your case, input data, x), it can predict what the "answer" (in your case: output data, y) should be.<n><n>A neural network is a classifier, and is one example of a classifier.<n><n>The goal would be to find the training data that when it is loaded into your network in the form of input X then gets output Y and you will try to make your network classify as much the class of Y as possible. You will be using labels(the "answers") for your X and Y data points. You will make sure that your network has no input/output mismatches, that is, that the X=Y, otherwise your network would not be a function.<n><n>For example, given the following table data, how are you to decide that it is a table tennis ball is bigger than a basketball?<n><n>\begin{code}<n>ball_a ball_b<n>bigger bigger<n>same same<n>same bigger<n>same same<n>\end{code}<n><n>Do all of these entries indicate what is "bigger" (the output) to be "bigger" (input)? No, you shouldn't be making this inference.<n><n>Instead you

You may not be familiar with these clues but in this problem set you can use them. <n><n>* **R:** When there are double words, the double word does not change. <n><n>* ***R1:** When a clue has the same letter at the beginning & end, the last & first letters are the same. <n><n>* If the first & last letters are the same: <n><n>* If there is an's' on the first letter: the last letter is either 'd' or 'e' <n><n>Rule: The rule was made for the letters in the clues.<n><n>Instruction for 4 & 5: The clue is the same as the word the person wanted to say.<n><n><n>**Input1:** “Where would I go to find information about a certain product?”<n><n>**Output:** “F: store”<n><n>**Input2: A: what is made the least often? ### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Fabric is cut to order at what type of seller? Choices:  A: curtains B: tailor shop C: clothing store D: sewing room E: hardware store<n>Output: B: tailor shop<n><n>Input: Where are you if your reading magazines while waiting for a vehicle on rails? Choices:  A: vegetables B: market C: doctor D: train station E: bookstore<n>Output: D: train station<n><n>Input: What would need oil to be used? Choices:  A: ground B: human  body C: repair shop D: combustion engines E: service station<n>Output: D: combustion engines<n><n>Input: What is person probably feeling that plans on stopping being married to their spouse? Choices:  A: detachment B: bankruptcy C: sad D: fights E: wrong<n>Output: A: detachment<n><n>Input: What could you use to store a clock? Choices:  A: shelf B: own bedroom C: desk D: wall E: car<n>Output: A: shelf<n><n>Input: The person put on lotion, what did they want? Choices:  A: fresh smell B: good credit C: smooth skin D: fresh produce E: headache<n>Output: C: smooth skin<n><n>Input:The wheel was loose, and threatened to fall off when they were what? Choices:  A: footloose B: sailing C: fast D: tighten E: bind<n>Output:		B: sailing<n><n>Input: The child was excited from the what? Choices: A: birthday celebration B: sports team C: fireworks D: haircut E: holiday<n>Output: D: haircut<n><n>Input: The dog and owner were lost when they were wandering about what at night? Choices:  a: woods B: parking lot C: road D: suburb E: village<n>Output: A: woods<n><n>Input: Where did the customer place the clothing? Choices: A. bedroom B. bathroom C. closet D. bedding store E. in the trunk<n>Output: C: closet<n><n>Input: A person is doing the what? Choices (a): washing windows (b) washing laundry (c) washing hair (d) washing car (e) washing dishes (f) washing hands<n>Output: A: washing windows<n><n>## Solution<n>```Python<n>#############################################################################<n>#                        Functions                                         #<n>######################################################################<n><n>def checkSold(s, word):<n>    if s.startswith(word):<n>        return True<n>    return False<n><n>def checkWords(wlst):<n>    for w in wlst:<n>        for i in ["bedroom", "bathroom", "closet", "bedding store", "own bedroom"]:<n>            if checkSold(i,w):<n>                return True<n>    return True<n><n>def checkLocation(location, s, wlst, a):<n>    if s in location:<n>        for w in wlst[:]: <n>        if checkLocation(location, w[a], s, wlst) == True:<n>            return True<n>        return False<n>    return True<n>def matchTrivium(wordlist, location):<n>    if not checkWords(wordlist):<n>        return False<n><n>    if checkLocation(location,"", wordlist, 0):<n>        return True <n>    else: <n>        return False<n>```

### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Fabric is cut to order at what type of seller? Choices:  A: curtains B: tailor shop C: clothing store D: sewing room E: hardware store<n>Output: B: tailor shop<n><n>Input: Where are you if your reading magazines while waiting for a vehicle on rails? Choices:  A: ground B: human  body C: repair shop D: combustion engines E: service station<n>Output: D: combustion engines<n><n>Input: What is person probably feeling that plans on stopping being married to their spouse? Choices:  A: detachment B: bankruptcy C: sad D: fights E: wrong<n>Output: A: detachment<n><n>Input: What could you use to store a clock? Choices:  A: shelf B: own bedroom C: desk D: wall E: car<n>Output: A: shelf<n><n>Input: The person put on lotion, what did they want? You took a look at a clock which was very close. What do you want? Choices:A: tailored pants B: tailor shopC: fast D: close E: pants<n>Output: A: tailored pants<n><n>Input: What did person put on after a shower? Choices:  Oil is needed for what, but not a car?  A: combustion engine B: service  station C: doctor's office D: railway E: vegetable stand<n>Output: B: service station<n><n><br><br>## Python Code:<n><n>```python<n>import sys<n><n><n>def solve(input_lines):<n><n>    mydict = {<n>        # ['oil', 'tailor', 'person']<n>        'oil': ['combustion engine','repair shop', 'clock'],<n>        'person': ['detachment', 'bankruptcy', 'human body', 'fights'],<n>        'tailor': ['clothing store', 'tailor shop', 'curtains','vegetables'],<n>        'doctor': ['train station','market', 'headache','vegetable stand'],<n>        'detachment': ['smooth skin', 'wall', 'desk', 'credit'],<n>    }<n><n>    def answer(inp):<n><n>        if inp!= 'A' and mydict[inp] == [] or not mydict[inp]:<n>            print(inp)<n>        else:<n>            print(mydict[inp][0])<n><n>    for x, y in enumerate(input_lines): # x is the index of the line, and y is the answer string<n><n>        if x % 2: # the even number<n><n>            print(' ')<n><n>            if x == 0:<n>                answer(y) # run the function answer(y)<n>            for y in mydict.keys():<n>                if y in y:  # if the words you want to test are in y, for loop is entered<n>                    answer(y)<n><n>            else:<n>                continue<n>        else: # the odd number, so it's not going to run the answer function<n><n>            for y in y:<n>

### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Fabric is cut to order at what type of seller? Choices:  A: curtains B: tailor shop C: clothing store D: sewing room E: hardware store<n>Output: B: tailor shop<n><n>Input: Where are you if your reading magazines while waiting for a vehicle on rails? Choices:  A: ground B: human  body C: repair shop D: combustion engines E: service station<n>Output: D: combustion engines<n><n>Input: What is person probably feeling that plans on stopping being married to their spouse? Choices:  A: detachment B: bankruptcy C: sad D: fights E: wrong<n>Output: A: detachment<n><n>Input: What could you use to store a clock? Choices:  A: shelf B: own bedroom C: desk D: wall E: car<n>Output: A: shelf<n><n>Input: The person put on lotion, what did they want? Choices: 1. find out what people like 2. ask people to speak up 3. try to help others 4. get the information together 5. be a good listener 6. help organize 7. take the lead<n>Output: 6. help organise<n><n># 1<n><n>---<n><n>```python<n>class Solution(object):<n>  def canRotate(self, matrix):<n>    """<n>    :type matrix: List[List[int]]<n>    :rtype: bool<n>    """<n>    return not any((x > 0) for y, row in enumerate(matrix) for x in row)<n><n>```<n><n>## Solution 1<n><n>We rotate matrix by 90 degrees such that the direction of each of the main diagonal is same.<n><n>```python<n>if canRotate(matrix):<n>    for row in matrix:<n>        if len(row) > 1:<n>            # Rotating matrix by 90o<n>            if matrix[idx][-1] < matrix[idx][-2]:<n>                row[-1:][::-1] += row[:-1]<n>                idx += 1<n>            else:<n>                row[0], row[-1] = row[-1], row[0]<n>```<n>## Solution 2<n><n>**My solution here in O(n) time**<n><n>**My solution is to add one more row after the last index in the matrix. By doing so we will break the cycle of the index.**<n><n>```python<n># This function helps you to detect if you can rotate<n>def index(row):<n>  return (row[1] > row[2]) and (row[2] > row[3]) and (row[3] > row[4]) and (row[4] > row[5])<n><n># This function will break the loop and take out the new index<n># 1. First find first number in the row<n># 2. Next compare it to the n-1 th element in the previous row<n># 3. If it is less then add one row after n<n>def addRow(row, mat):<n>  global i<n>  n = len(mat)<n>  i = 0<n>  if index(row

Choices:  A: ground B: human  body C: repair shop D: combustion engines E: service station<n>Output: D: combustion engines<n><n>Input: What is person probably feeling that plans on stopping being married to their spouse? Choices:  A: kept at accountant B: purse C: desk drawer D: bank E: keeping track of expenses<n>Output:		D: bank<n><n>Input: You need to use gas if you are going to do what? Choices: 	A: go to the doctor 	B: to the hair salon 	C: work out 	D: to run errands 	E: visiting friends 	F: drive to school<n>Output: D: to run errands<n><n>Input: You would most likely find who are in the grocer? Choices: 1. A: vegetables 2. B: cakes 3. C: fruit 4. D: bread 5. E: meat 6. F: produce<n>Output: F: produce<n><n>Input:  if you are feeling blue because of cold, you would probably need to use what? Choices: a. heater b. fan c. ice d. snow boots <n>Output: a. heater<n><n>Input: If you want to travel to a rural town in your Rugged country, which of these is likely the best car to use? Choices:  a. sedan b. truck c. van d. off-road vehicle<n>Output: d. off-road vehicled. off-road vehicle is an example of rugged car.<n><n># Important Information: For more information, go to https://github.com/davidevers/LeetCode-Solutions<n><n>############################################### Solutions Start ###############################################<n>class Solution:<n>    def doubleDiskSpace(self, disk_count: int, disk_size: int) -> int:<n>        if disk_size == 0:<n>            return 0<n><n>        return disk_size // disk_count - (disk_size % disk_count == 0) and disk_size - (disk_size - disk_size // disk.count)<n><n><n>def main():<n>    solution = Solution()<n>    print(solution.doubleDiskSpace(100, 100))<n>    print(solutions.doubleDiskSpace_(100, 97))<n><n><n>if __name__ == '__main__':<n>    main()<n>
